LEPTOSPIROSIS - KENYA (WESTERN DISTRICTS) (02)
**********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: Fri, 18 Jun 2004
From: S K Sharif <sksharif@ikenya.com>

The death toll due to the outbreak of leptospirosis in Bungoma District in
Western Province is 12. The source of infection is due to untreated water.
The schools and the communities have been drawing water from various
rivers and have not been treating the water. The river waters had also been
contaminated by untreated sewerage which was discharged into the river in
April this year.
The diagnosis of leptospirosis was confirmed by serological tests. The
death toll reported by newspapers includes deaths due to other causes. The
prolonged duration of the outbreak (since May 2004) may have been due to
continued exposure to contaminated water. The ministry is still awaiting
confirmation about the animal source of contamination. The most likely
animal source is suspected to be rodents. The area where the outbreak
occurred is a swamp area.
Leptospirosis in humans has been reported in Kenya in Nyanza Province and
Kwale District in Coast Province. In both these areas it was associated
with sugar cane growing.
--
Dr S K Sharif
Kenya Ministry of Health
<sksharif@ikenya.com>
