Date: Fri, 18 Jun 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AllAfrica.com and The East African Standard (Nairobi) [edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200406180322.html>

Only 12 people have died from swamp fever disease in Chesamisi in Western
Province, the government said Thu, 17 Jun 2004. Disputing Press reports
that 26 people had succumbed to the disease known as leptospirosis,
Director of Medical Services James Nyikal termed the reports misleading.
The new figures emerged as the government announced that it had sent a team
of medical personnel to help in surveillance, investigation and health
education. "We have, for instance, sent our public health officers to
educate villagers on the disease and preventive measures," said
Nyikal. Another team was specifically tasked with finding the source of
the disease in the area, which has been put under a state of high alert.
Of the dead, 6 were students of Chesamisi High Boys School while 2 were
from Chesamisi Primary School. The others were villagers. Nyikal put the
number of those admitted to hospital at 86. "A total of 69 Chesamis high
school students are admitted to Webuye sub-district hospital in serious but
stable condition," he said.
11 villagers are admitted to the hospital, 2 at Eldoret's Moi Teaching and
Referral Hospital Eldoret and another 4 at Cherangany Nursing Home in Kitale.
[Byline: William Faria And Vincent Bartoo]
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[ProMED thanks Dr. Sharif from the Kenyan Department of Health for
clarifying the extent and probable source of the serologically confirmed
outbreak. A recent report from Ethiopia found that 47.5 percent of febrile
outpatients who did not have malaria were seropositive for leptospirosis
(1). In other countries on the African Continent, the report cites
seroprevalence rates for leptospirosis were 33 percent in Ghana and 18
percent in Nigeria.
Readers should note that in epidemic leptospirosis on the Indian
subcontinent (2) and in the Americas (3, 4), severe respiratory disease was
found to be a prominent manifestation of the infection.
1. Yimer E, Koopman S, Messele T, et al. Human leptospirosis, in Ethiopia:
a pilot study in Wonji. Ethiop J Health Dev 2004;18:48-51.
2. De A, Varaiya A, Pujari A, et al. An outbreak of leptospirosis in
Mumbai. Ind J Med Microbiol 2000;20:153-55.
3. Trevejo RT, Rigau-Perez JG, Ashford DA, et al. Epidemic leptospirosis
associated with pulmonary hemorrhage-Nicaragua, 1995. J Infect Dis
1998;178:1457-63.
4. Ko AI, Galvao Reis M, Ribeiro Dourado CM, ewt al. Urban epidemic of
severe leptospirosis in Brazil. Lancet 1999;354:820-25.
-Mod.LL]
